AFTER stunning many by walking away with the Promoter of the Year Award at Boxing SA&rsquo;s gala Awards ceremony at the Inkosi Albert Luthuli International Convention Centre in Durban, KZN, last week Friday, Andre Thysse, has hit the ground running.The former South African and Commonwealth super-middleweight champion is now preparing for two tournaments which are a week apart.The Real Steel Promotions boss kicks off his boxing calendar with a six-bout tournament on 25 March, which will feature two regional titles: a WBA Pan African and an African Boxing Union (ABU). The Boksburg-based promoter said he will also stage a development tournament a week later.In the Promoter of the Year category, he was up against the likes of East London&rsquo;s Ayanda Matiti and Mbali &ldquo;Don Queen&rdquo; Zantsi from Mthatha.Matiti has been flying Mzansi&rsquo;s flag high in the international arena.&ldquo;This award came with more responsibilities, which are to continue staging quality tournaments.&ldquo;People have put a block on my head. Although I was not expecting to win, it was great feeling to take the award home,&rdquo; he said.He told SunSport: &ldquo;Now, I&rsquo;m working hard to maintain that status of being a top promoter in the country and I start my new year boxing calendar with two tournaments which are a week apart.&rdquo;Thysse, who acquired the international boxing promoting license last year has been nurturing young stars through his development tournaments for the past four years.Now the businessman says he wants to promote world titles this year.&ldquo;We&rsquo;re working towards having an international title on our programme this year. We know it won&rsquo;t be an easy ride, but we&rsquo;re determined to win,&rdquo; he said.